04899nam a22005775i 9780822392842DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223928427 a10.1515/97808223928422doi  a(DE-B1597)552546  a(OCoLC)1202625357  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHV9592.5.A77bS2713 2010 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a365/.45092aB2221 aSattamini, Lina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Mother's Cry :bA Memoir of Politics, Prison, and Torture under the Brazilian Military Dictatorship /cLina Sattamini; James N. Green. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (208 p.) :bfrontispiece  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Political Chronology of the Brazilian Military Dictatorship, 1964-85 -- tIntroduction The Personal and the Political under the Brazilian Military Regime -- tA Memoir We Must Never Forget -- t1 The Beginning -- t2 Operation Bandeirantes -- t3 The Military Hospital -- t4 Incommunicado -- t5 Our First Visit -- t6 Still Imprisoned -- t7 Transferred to Rio -- t8 Solitude -- t9 Support in the United States -- t10 My Return to Brazil -- t11 The Saga Continues -- t12 Anguish -- t13 Despair -- t14 Freedom -- t15 Exile -- t16 Protest -- t17 Recovery -- t18 Continuing the Struggle -- t19 Another Martyr of the Dictatorship -- t20 In Search of a Permanent Visa -- t21 Returning Home -- t22 Never Forgetting -- tEpilogue No path for the righteous traveler -- tEditor's Postscript -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the late 1960s and early 1970s, Brazil's dictatorship arrested, tortured, and interrogated many people it suspected of subversion; hundreds of those arrested were killed in prison. In May 1970, Marcos P. S. Arruda, a young political activist, was seized in São Paulo, imprisoned, and tortured. A Mother's Cry is the harrowing story of Marcos's incarceration and his family's efforts to locate him and obtain his release. Marcos's mother, Lina Penna Sattamini, was living in the United States and working for the U.S. State Department when her son was captured. After learning of his arrest, she and her family mobilized every resource and contact to discover where he was being held, and then they launched an equally intense effort to have him released. Marcos was freed from prison in 1971. Fearing that he would be arrested and tortured again, he left the country, beginning eight years of exile.Lina Penna Sattamini describes her son's tribulations through letters exchanged among family members, including Marcos, during the year that he was imprisoned. Her narrative is enhanced by Marcos's account of his arrest, imprisonment, and torture. James N. Green's introduction provides an overview of the political situation in Brazil, and Latin America more broadly, during that tumultuous era. In the 1990s, some Brazilians began to suggest that it would be best to forget the trauma of that era and move on. Lina Penna Sattamini wrote her memoir as a protest against historical amnesia. First published in Brazil in 2000, A Mother's Cry is testimonial literature at its best. It conveys the experiences of a family united by love and determination during years of political repression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aPolitical persecutionzBrazilvCase studies. 0aPolitical prisonerszBrazilvBiography. 0aTorture victimszBrazilvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aArruda, Marcos P. S.1 aGreen, James N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNielson, Rex P.08iTitle is part of eBook